CSS Modeling Background: Criminal Preference

  • Criminal Preference: According to crime pattern theory and rational choice theory, criminals have definite preferences about the features of the locations where they commit crimes.

    • Spatial:
      • Travel distance from hide to crime
      • Distance from reacting forces (police stations, TCPs)
      • Distance to key spatial features (streets, banks, bar)
    • Demographic/Economic (Cultural):
      • Burglaries in high end neighborhoods
      • Sunni vs. Shia violence in Baghdad
      • Tribal/Gang affiliation


  • Situational Crime Prevention: identifies why crime occurs in specific settings and seeks solutions that reflect the nature of those settings.

CSS Modeling Background: Spatial Choice

CSS Modeling Process

  1. Import and Organize Shapefiles (Munge)

  2. Develop CSS Modeling Data Frames (Munge)

  3. Develop CSS Models (Model)

  4. Evaluate CSS Model Performance (Model)

  5. Develop Maps of CSS Model Prediction (Visualize)

Example Application: Criminal Gangs (Santa Ana)

Can we use spatial information about previous crimes to predict where criminal gangs will commit crimes in the future (applicable to targeting, resource allocation, etc.)?

Import and Organize Shapefiles (1 of 7)

Shapefiles used for this analysis include:

  • SA_Outline: an outline of the City of Santa Ana, California

  • GangPoints: a gang intelligence map containing the point locations (addresses) for some of the criminal gangs in the city.

  • GangTerritory: a gang intelligence map containing the "claimed" gang territories for some of the criminal gangs in the city.

  • Block_Groups: demographic information at the Census block group level from the 2000 Census

  • Streets: a line shapefile street map of the City of Santa Ana, California

  • GangIncidents: a point shapefile of the locations of criminal incidents by the six most violent gangs in the city

  • Grid_Points: a point shapefile of a point grid at a high resolution over the City of Santa Ana, which will be used for modeling and visualization

Geographic Coordinate Systems Primer

  • The following are two common types of coordinate systems used in a geographic information system (GIS):

    • A global or spherical coordinate system such as latitude-longitude. These are often referred to as geographic coordinate systems.
    • A projected coordinate system such as universal transverse Mercator (UTM), Albers Equal Area, or Robinson, all of which (along with numerous other map projection models) provide various mechanisms to project maps of the earth's spherical surface onto a two-dimensional Cartesian coordinate plane. Projected coordinate systems are referred to as map projections.

  • Coordinate systems (both geographic and projected) provide a framework for defining real-world locations.

  • If your shapefiles are not in the same coordinate system/projection, they will not line up.







Definitions Source: resources.esri.com

Import and Organize Shapefiles (4 of 7)

To read the coordinate system in a shapefile:

proj4string(SA.Outline)
## [1] "+proj=lcc +lat_1=32.78333333333333 +lat_2=33.88333333333333 +lat_0=32.16666666666666 +lon_0=-116.25 +x_0=2000000 +y_0=500000.0000000002 +datum=NAD83 +units=us-ft +no_defs +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0"
proj4string(Gang.Territory)
## [1] "+proj=longlat +datum=NAD83 +no_defs +ellps=GRS80 +towgs84=0,0,0"

To transform a shapefile to a new coordinate system:

Gang.Territory<-spTransform(Gang.Territory, CRS(proj4string(SA.Outline)))

Develop CSS Modeling Data Frames

  • Dependent (Response) Variable: incidents (Response = 1) vs. null grid (Response = 0).

  • Independent (Predictor) Variables: incidents and null grid given feature space, categorical, and demographic attributes of their locations in geography.

Feature Space Predictors (1 of 2)

Feature space is a higher dimensional representation of the position of an incident. Rather than an incident being located by X and Y coordinate, it is located by the Euclidean distance to each of the features in the feature space dataset (gang territory, gang conflict, street, etc.)

Feature Space Predictors (2 of 2)

Response<-data.frame(rep(1, length(Incidents@data[,1])))
colnames(Response)<-"Response"
Inc.Data<-Incidents
Inc.Data@data<-Response
DistToGangPnts<-nncross(as.ppp(Inc.Data), as.ppp(Gang.Points))[,1]
hist(DistToGangPnts)

Categorical Predictors

Territory.Check<-over(Inc.Data, Gang.Territory)[,1]
InGangTerr<-vector(mode="numeric", length=length(Territory.Check))
InGangTerr[!is.na(Territory.Check)]<-1

The code block uses the over() and the !is.na() functions to assign a categorical value of 1 to any location that falls within a gang territory and a categorical value of 0 (by default) to any location that does not.

Demographic Predictors

We can also use the over() function to assign a point layer (either incidents or null grid) the demographic values of the census block group they fall within:

Inc.Demographics<-over(Inc.Data, Block.Groups)
#Create Predictor Matrix for Incidents
Inc.Pred.Matrix<-cbind(Response, DistToGangPnts, DistToStreet, InGangTerr, 
                       Inc.Demographics[,10:52])
Inc.Data@data<-Inc.Pred.Matrix

Train vs. Test vs. Model vs. Predict Datasets

For CSS Models, we generate four different kinds of datasets:

  • Train vs. Test Dataset: We split our data between training and testing datasets so that we objectively compare the predictive performance of modeling approaches.

    • Incidents from 1996-1998 for training data

    • Incidents from 1999-2000 as the test data

    • Sample (about 5000 points) from the null grid to get a representation for places where crime did not happen.


  • Model Dataset: We use all of our incident data and a sample (about 5000 points) from the null grid to develop the model we will use to make predictions (build the best model you can).


  • Predict Dataset: We use the model generated using our Model Dataset to predict on the null grid to generate a "threat map", or predictive hot-spot map that shows where incidents are likely to occur in the future.

CSS Models

Initial Model Fitting on Train Data:

# Logistic Regression on Feature-Space Predictors
Model.1<-glm(Response ~ DistToGangPnts + DistToStreet + InGangTerr, family="binomial", data=Train.Data)

# Stepwise Logistic Regression on Feature-Space Predictors
Model.2<-glm(Response ~., family="binomial", data=Train.Data)
Model.3<-step(Model.2)

# Random Forest Model
Model.4<-randomForest(as.factor(Response) ~., data=Train.Data)

Prediction on Test Data:

# Logistic Regression Models use invlogit() and predict()
M1.prediction<-as.vector(invlogit(predict(Model.1, newdata=Test.Data)))
M3.prediction<-as.vector(invlogit(predict(Model.3, newdata=Test.Data)))

# Random Forest predicts probability for both "classes" - you must refine 
M4.prediction<-predict(Model.4, newdata=Test.Data, type="prob")[,2]

Surveillance Plot: Evaluating CSS Model Performance (Test Dataset)

Predict Using Best Modeling Approach and All Your Data

######### Build model on ALL Observations
Model.Data<-rbind(Null.Train@data, Inc.Data@data)

# Build Final Model on Model.Data dataframe
Model.5<-randomForest(as.factor(Response) ~., data=Model.Data)

# First do the prediction on the grid points to confirm class
head(predict(Model.5, newdata=Null.Data, type="prob"))

# Predict on grid - note Class "1" is in column 2
Prediction<-predict(Model.5, newdata=Null.Data, type="prob")[,2]
Prediction[is.na(Prediction)]<-0  #Points outside of Santa Ana are NA

# Add prediction to Null.Data data frame (for visualization)                   
Null.Data@data<-cbind(Null.Data@data, Prediction)

Generate a Raster Image of the Prediction

library(raster)
r <- raster(ncol=200, nrow=200)
extent(r) <- extent(SA.Outline)
Prediction.Raster<- rasterize(Null.Data, r, 'Prediction')

Use Leaflet for Interactive Map

library(leaflet)
library(RColorBrewer)
#Set the projection for our raster and street map                  
crs(Prediction.Raster) <- sp::CRS(proj4string(SA.Outline))    
#Add color palette using RColorBrewer
palette<-brewer.pal(8, "Reds")
pal <- colorNumeric(palette, values(Prediction.Raster),
                    na.color = "transparent")
#Define Lat-Long for our plot using extent()
Latitude=mean(extent(Streets)[1:2])
Longitude=mean(extent(Streets)[3:4])
                       
my.map<-leaflet() %>%
   setView(Latitude, Longitude, zoom = 12) %>%
   addProviderTiles("Stamen.Toner") %>%
   addRasterImage(Prediction.Raster, colors = pal, opacity = .8) %>%
   addLegend(pal = pal, values = values(Prediction.Raster),
         title = "Prediction") 
my.map   #to plot the map

Summary

  • Munge
    • readOGR() for shapefile importation
    • proj4string() for organizing your projections/coordinate systems
    • Use plotting to make sure your shapefiles line up
  • Model
    • Train vs. Test vs. Model vs. Predict Datasets
    • Surveillance plot for model evaluation (on test data set)
    • Predict using best modeling approach and all your data
  • Visualize
    • Basic plotting provides quick check
    • Provide interactivity and map orientation using leaflet()
